prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 7 dust and line; Fields 1-100
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We propose to measure the dust continuum and spectral line emission for 251 young stars in the 0.5-Myr-old Orion NGC 2024 cluster in order to determine disk masses, sizes and gas content and by comparison with the 2-Myr-old Orion Nebula cluster, constrain disk lifetimes in high-mass star forming regions.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We request observations with ALMA using its Band 7 (856 micron) receivers to measure the dust and gas in protoplanetary disks around 251 young stars in the Orion NGC 2024 cluster. We will survey 100 pointings to a depth of 1 sigma ~ 0.2 mJy/beam (3 sigma ~ 0.3 Mjup) at the pointing center (0.6 Mjup at the beam edges), which can be achieved in 2 minutes per pointing (3.3 hours on-source) as calculated by the ALMA OT, using 2nd octile weather conditions. Simulations of our proposed ALMA Cycle 2 observations confirm that adequate uv-coverage for imaging in NGC 2024 is obtained in 2 minutes. We request 0.4 arcsec FWHM resolution to distinguish individual disks, which are clustered together near the O-star, IRS2b (see Figure 1), and to resolve dust-disk emission for the largest disks. Our requested observational setup is identical to our Cycle 0 and Cycle 1 projects in the Orion Nebula cluster, which will allow us to probe the same spatial scales, to a similar depth and at the same observing frequency. These observations cannot be carried out at lower frequencies as the ionized gas surrounding photoevaporating disks in high-mass star forming regions can swamp the thermal dust emission from disks even at 1.3 mm (Mann \& Williams 2009, Eisner et al. 2008).
We will also target the CO J=3-2, HCN J=4-3, HCO+ J=4-3 and CS J=7-6 lines. The expected line widths are ~3-10 km/s, so we will use a channel spacing of 0.244 MHz, which will be Hanning smoothed in the correlator to a spectral resolution of 0.42 km/s. Diameters of the target disks likely range between 0.1 arcsec - 2.5 arcsec (the resolution of the SMA observations), or 40-1000 AU at 400 pc, the distance to Orion. If a typical 20 K Taurus disk was placed at the distance of Orion in a 0.4 arcsec beam, and an appropriate beam filling factor was applied, the observed line temperatures would range between 1.3 K to 20 K. The ALMA sensitivity calculator estimates an rms noise temperature of 1.3 K for these observations, which is sufficient to detect even cold molecular gas in these disks.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Protoplanetary disks are the sites where new Solar systems form. While numerous disk studies have focused on nearby regions of low-mass star formation, stars rarely form in such isolated environments. Most stars, including our Sun, form in clustered, high-mass star forming regions. For this reason, we propose to survey 251 protoplanetary disks in the 0.5-Myr-old NGC 2024 cluster in Orion in order to study fundamental disk properties in high-mass star forming regions. The proposed observations will reveal the full range of masses of the youngest protoplanetary disks surveyed to date in a high-mass star forming region. We will measure the masses and sizes of numerous disks and attempt to detect molecular gas in the NGC 2024 disks for the first time. We will also track the evolution of disk properties between the 0.5-Myr-old NGC 2024 and 2-Myr-old Orion Nebula clusters, in order to constrain disk lifetimes, and hence planet formation timescales in rich clusters. And ultimately, by surveying a large number of disks around very young stars, we can determine the overall fraction of stars with the potential to form planetary systems like our own.
